📌 Deployment Basics – GS-Level Understanding
1. Core Concept
Deployment is the process of making your application available in production for end-users.
Key goals:
Reliability
Scalability
Observability
Minimal downtime
2. Types of Deployment
Type	Description	GS-Level Notes
Manual	Copy files, start server manually	Rarely used in enterprise; not scalable
Automated CI/CD	Build → Test → Deploy pipelines	Standard at GS and fintech; ensures reproducibility
Blue-Green	Two identical environments; switch traffic	Minimal downtime; rollback ready
Canary	Release to small subset first	Monitor errors before full rollout
Rolling	Gradual upgrade of instances	No downtime; smooth scaling
Immutable Deployments	Deploy new container/image instead of patching	Works with Docker/Kubernetes
3. Deployment Best Practices
Use containers (Docker) for reproducibility
Automate via CI/CD pipelines (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab)
Health checks and readiness probes to detect failing services
Environment-specific configuration via env variables or ConfigMaps
Rollback strategy in case of failure
Versioning images and API endpoints
Python Deployment Example (FastAPI + Uvicorn)
# main.py
from fastapi import FastAPI

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/health")
def health_check():
    return {"status": "healthy"}

@app.get("/greeting")
def greeting(name: str = "GS Trader"):
    return {"message": f"Hello, {name}"}

Deployment with Docker & Uvicorn

# Build container
docker build -t gs-app:1.0 .

# Run container in production mode
docker run -d -p 8000:8000 --name gs-app gs-app:1.0

# Health check endpoint
curl http://localhost:8000/health

GS-Level Tips:

Use -d for detached mode in production
Use Docker Compose or Kubernetes for multi-service deployments
Mount logs to persistent storage for auditing
